student performance prediction system project theoretical summary

The Student Performance Prediction System applies machine learning to forecast student outcomes based on academic features.

It uses Study Hours, Attendance, Previous Marks, Assignments, and Internal Marks as input variables.

The target variable is Final_Result (Pass/Fail), enabling classification tasks.

Multiple models are implemented — Logistic Regression, Decision Tree, Naive Bayes, and SVM — for comparative analysis.

The system provides a Streamlit dashboard for interactive data entry and visualization.

Graphs such as Study Hours vs Marks and Attendance vs Result highlight performance trends.

The project identifies at‑risk students with low attendance or failing predictions.

It demonstrates the integration of data preprocessing, model training, and visualization in a single workflow.

The system is designed to be examiner‑friendly, with clear outputs and structured results.

Academically, it contributes to education analytics, offering a scalable approach to student evaluation.
